<p>To understand how we come to know and learn, it’s helpful to look at the philosophical ideas that laid the groundwork for modern learning theories. These early thinkers explored the origins of knowledge and the ways in which humans acquire understanding. Let’s take a brief journey through the foundational ideas of three pivotal philosophers who shaped the way we think about learning.</p>



<p>Picture <strong>Plato</strong> sitting in his academy in ancient Greece, proposing a radical idea: we&#8217;re all born with knowledge already inside us. For Plato, learning goes beyond absorbing new information &#8211; to even uncover wisdom that&#8217;s been there all along. </p>



<p>Enter <strong>Aristotle</strong>, Plato&#8217;s star student, with a completely different take. He argues that we learn through our senses and experiences. For Aristotle, knowledge comes from observing the world around us and making connections. It&#8217;s like building a mental library, where each new experience adds another book to our collection.</p>



<p>Fast forward to <strong>John Locke</strong>, who takes an even bolder stance. He suggests we&#8217;re born with minds like blank slates &#8211; completely empty, waiting to be written on by experience. No pre-loaded knowledge, no innate ideas. Everything we know, we learn through interacting with the world.</p>



